item.title: Orange-Glazed Chicken Meatballs Recipe!
item.description:
https://www.triedandtruerecipe.com/orange-glazed-chicken-meatballs/ Orange sauce: 4 ounces fresh-squeezed orange juice 2 tablespoons Shaoxing wine 2 tablespoons rice vinegar 4 tablespoons light brown sugar 2 tablespoons tamari 1 tablespoon sesame oil 1 tablespoon chili oil, optional 1 tablespoon cornstarch ¼ cup water Chicken meatballs and yu choy: 1 pound ground chicken 4 cloves garlic, peeled and minced 1-inch piece of ginger, peeled and minced 1 shallot, peeled and minced ¼ cup tamari 1 egg ¾ cup panko, plus more if needed 2 teaspoons sesame oil 2 tablespoons neutral oil, for frying 4 scallions, trimmed and minced; white and green parts kept separate 4 ounces yu choy, trimmed and roughly chopped Salt to taste For serving: Cooked white rice Sesame seeds Make the sauce: Whisk together all the ingredients for the sauce in a bowl until completely smooth. Set aside. Prepare the meatballs: Gather the ground chicken, minced garlic, ginger, shallot, tamari, and egg into a large bowl. Use a rubber spatula to mix until completely incorporated. Add the panko and mix with the spatula until combined. Form the mixture into tablespoon-sized meatballs. The meatballs may feel soft and not be perfectly firm, and it’s okay if they’re a little ragged around the edges. Transfer to a plate and refrigerate for 10 minutes. Fry the meatballs: Meanwhile, add 2 tablespoons neutral oil to a wide pot over medium heat. Allow the oil to preheat for 5 minutes as the meatballs refrigerate. Add the meatballs to the pot, cooking in batches if needed, for 3 to 5 minutes per side until browned on all sides. Transfer to a plate. Simmer the meatballs: Carefully wipe out any excess oil from the pot. Return the meatballs to the pot and pour the sauce on top. Turn the heat to medium-high. As soon as the sauce begins to bubble, reduce the heat to low and cover. Simmer for 20 to 25 minutes until the meatballs reach 165ºF when pierced with an instant-read thermometer. Finish the meatballs: Remove the lid from the pot. Add the white parts of the scallions and the chopped yu choy along with a pinch of salt. Cover and simmer for 5 minutes until the greens wilt and the sauce loosens up from the water released from the vegetables. If the sauce is too thick for your liking, add a splash or two of water after simmering. Taste and season. To serve: Spoon the meatballs over cooked white rice. Serve with the reserved minced scallion greens and sesame seeds on top. Enjoy!
The whole process!

item.title: Fuck it all!
item.description: I know, credit is a made up joke that doesn’t actually do shit for anyone. I have an “exceptional” credit score and I’ll never be able to buy a house by myself anyway. But fuck this. Fuck all of it. I’m a single bitch with zero family, raw dogging this whole life completely by myself. This felt like an accomplishment and I wanted to celebrate it (because dog knows we only celebrate women for marriage and birth). Definitely puts a damper on my solo party, but fuck if I’ll let it rain on my parade. But still, eat my whole ass, and not even in a fun way! FP Edit: I made and posted this in a fit of rage after paying my credit card and seeing the hit. Did not expect it to blow up like this so quickly. I understand how credit works. I understand why the ding happened. I understand it is a predatory and racist system meant to only benefit people with money. The point of the post was to lament about a fucked up system. And to say that I am still fucking proud of myself to be where I am in this life given the circumstances that I’ve been dealt. I was born and raised in poverty by functionally illiterate alcoholics/addicts. I have no family at all and no partner. I have a severe chronic illness that is still destroying my body. I’ve done some of the hardest shit of my life in the past year and a half. The point is that I’m proud of myself. I’ve never had anyone to be proud of me. Literally never heard that from anyone until a good homie in CO told me he was recently. I’ve spent the majority of my life scraping and scrapping in survival mode. And I’m still here, fighting to live the fullest and most beautiful life that I can. So thank you to the small handful of folks who could see that before this edit. Much love!
